    {
      "text": "A 45-year-old male presents to the dermatology clinic with a complaint of red scaly lesion on his lower back. On examination,  a well-demarcated, erythematous lesion measuring 4 cm in diameter with silvery scales on the surface is seen. What is the most likely diagnostic skin lesion present?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 0,
          "text": "Pustule"
        },
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "Plaque"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "Nodule"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "Wheal"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 1,
      "solution": "<p><strong>Correct Answer: B) Plaque</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>Explanation:</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>The <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"d5e7bb15851692777191b39417c26a\">lesion</span> is suggestive of <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"af71c1668e169277719542cf8f1364\">plaque</span> in psoriasis. Plaques are elevated <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"89aa50eac91692777184c8f668d2cf\">circumscribed</span> lesions > 1cm, <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"af71c1668e169277719542cf8f1364\">Plaque</span> in <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"8b9f55244b1692777196b5ddb9a6bf\">psoriasis</span> is characterized by silvery scales on a thickened, erythematous base. Depending on the underlying cause, these lesions can be pink, red, brown, or skin-colored. Some common causes of plaques include:\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li>Psoriasis</li>\n\t\t<li>Eczema (specifically <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"f92889f07116927771933df1244a14\">nummular</span> eczema)</li>\n\t\t<li>Lichen planus</li>\n\t\t<li>Seborrheic dermatitis</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div style=\"text-align:center\">\n<figure class=\"caption_element\" style=\"display:inline-block\"><img alt=\"\" data-author=\"Medmyco at English Wikipedia,\" data-hash=\"\" data-license=\"CC0 1.0\" data-source=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Microsporum_gypseum2418.JPG\" data-tags=\"\" height=\"862\" src=\"https://image.prepladder.com/content/HhevjNINU1EFCjIe5hRH1733921880.png\" width=\"888\" />\n<figcaption>{{caption_text}}</figcaption>\n</figure>\n</div>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>Pustule (Option A):</strong> A <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"0fd6c2af6d169277719639d2c79d03\">pustule</span> is a type of skin <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"d5e7bb15851692777191b39417c26a\">lesion</span> characterized by a small, <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"89aa50eac91692777184c8f668d2cf\">circumscribed</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"a1f256489a16927771870ddd296574\">elevation</span> of the skin that contains pus. Pustules are usually < 1cm in size</p>\n\n<div style=\"text-align:center\">\n<figure class=\"caption_element\" style=\"display:inline-block\"><img alt=\"\" data-author=\"Saurabh R. Patil,\" data-hash=\"\" data-license=\"CC BY-SA 3.0\" data-source=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:A_pustule.jpg\" data-tags=\"\" height=\"2749\" src=\"https://image.prepladder.com/content/uflPMh2cv36WOXZt3obo1733921979.png\" width=\"3986\" />\n<figcaption>{{caption_text}}</figcaption>\n</figure>\n</div>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>Nodule (Option C):</strong> Nodules are a type of skin <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"d5e7bb15851692777191b39417c26a\">lesion</span> characterized by solid, palpable, elevated masses that extend into the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"521e76df7d1692777186faf836b3f8\">dermis</span> or <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"d446e62c6c1692777199896fc1d4b9\">subcutaneous</span> tissue. They are >1 cm in size and range in depth from 1 to 10 mm.</p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<div style=\"text-align:center\">\n<figure class=\"caption_element\" style=\"display:inline-block\"><img alt=\"\" data-author=\"Kaminska-Winciorek, Grazyna & Wydmański, Jerzy & Januszewski, Krzysztof & Silny, Wojciech.\" data-hash=\"\" data-license=\"CC BY-NC-ND 3.0\" data-source=\"https://www.researchgate.net/figure/An-example-of-a-macroscopic-picture-of-a-meta-static-nodule-originating-from_fig5_281852640\" data-tags=\"\" height=\"3972\" src=\"https://image.prepladder.com/content/rXHKWHbshuIrSnDlzPIy1733922002.png\" width=\"3954\" />\n<figcaption>{{caption_text}}</figcaption>\n</figure>\n</div>\n\n<p><strong>Wheal (Option D): </strong>Wheals are a type of skin <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"d5e7bb15851692777191b39417c26a\">lesion</span> characterized by transient, edematous (swollen), elevated areas on the skin. These areas are typically pink or red and have well-defined borders.</p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<div style=\"text-align:center\">\n<figure class=\"caption_element\" style=\"display:inline-block\"><img alt=\"\" data-author=\"Allergyresearch,\" data-hash=\"\" data-license=\"CC BY-SA 4.0\" data-source=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Hives_Urticaria.jpg\" data-tags=\"\" height=\"2504\" src=\"https://image.prepladder.com/content/x4AD85gx8eohos4QkYhU1733922091.png\" width=\"3986\" />\n<figcaption>{{caption_text}}</figcaption>\n</figure>\n</div>",
