    {
      "text": "Which among the following is the pathway of epidermal cell migration during embryonic development and the most common disease associated with it?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 0,
          "text": "Langer lines - Gorlin syndrome"
        },
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "Blaschko lines - Incontinentia pigmenti"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "Langer lines - Neurofibromatosis type 1"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "Kraissl's lines - Linea Morphea"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 1,
      "solution": "<p><strong>Correct Answer: B) Blaschko lines - Incontinentia pigmenti</strong></p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>Explanation:</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>The described <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"d02067c4b51692777191b8eec8b062\">linear</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"dc75edd604169277719735ac5b4d5b\">rash</span> following a distinct geometric pattern with <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"635a7ea50e16927771944f08f17aed\">parallel</span> lines, often in a V-shaped distribution over the spine, is characteristic of <strong>Blaschko lines.</strong></li>\n\t<li>Blaschko lines represent a <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"3aa5abc2fa169277719488e088076d\">pathway</span> of normal <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"616d85c57416927771875ef23f6751\">epidermal</span> cell migration during embryonic development.</li>\n\t<li>Incontinentia pigmenti is an <strong>X-linked dominant</strong> disorder associated with Blaschko lines.</li>\n\t<li>It presents distinctive <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"94f1c8df1f1692777185bd6a7c3fff\">cutaneous</span> findings, including <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"d02067c4b51692777191b8eec8b062\">linear</span> vesicles, papules, and <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"30261213bf16927771898b5d2f245d\">hyperpigmentation</span> following the distribution of these lines.</li>\n\t<li>Other diseases associated with Blaschko disease are <strong>Epidermal naevi</strong> and <strong>Hypomelanosis of Ito.</strong> </li>\n</ul>\n\n<div style=\"text-align:center\">\n<figure class=\"caption_element\" style=\"display:inline-block\"><img alt=\"\" data-author=\"Kouzak, Samara & Mendes, Marcela & Costa, Izelda.\" data-hash=\"\" data-license=\"CC BY NC 3.0\" data-source=\"https://www.researchgate.net/figure/X-linked-Incontinentia-pigmenti-Pattern-type-1a-Blaschko-lines-narrow-bands_fig3_257074473\" data-tags=\"\" height=\"868\" src=\"https://image.prepladder.com/content/yvSqMFlhWvWlOoL3HxQE1733923347.png\" width=\"641\" />\n<figcaption>{{caption_text}}</figcaption>\n</figure>\n</div>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>Langer lines – Gorlin syndrome( Option A): Langer’s lines</strong>: Represent <strong>skin tension lines</strong> (used in surgery to guide incisions for better <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"9cf83937931692777188a014337dcf\">healing</span> and minimal scarring). Not related to <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"b22b2da273169277718771c2c57d09\">embryonic cell</span> migration. <strong>Gorlin syndrome (basal cell <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"d61ced9a671692777193e04a03c423\">nevus</span> syndrome)</strong> is associated with multiple <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"923af580cf16927771829606bce2a7\">basal</span> cell carcinomas, jaw cysts, and skeletal abnormalities — not with Langer lines.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Langer lines – Neurofibromatosis type 1</strong> (Option C): Again, <strong>Langer lines</strong> are about <strong>mechanical skin tension</strong>, not embryology. <strong>NF1</strong> manifests with café-au-lait spots, neurofibromas, Lisch nodules — these do <strong>not follow Langer’s lines</strong>.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Kraissl's lines (Option D)</strong> represent the relaxed skin tension lines of the breast and are pertinent in breast surgery planning. <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"d02067c4b51692777191b8eec8b062\">Linear</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"ea9cbd46e016927771925686939ea5\">morphea</span> is a <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"a1b06f401f1692777203a53393ba98\">form</span> of <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"8fb8df140b1692777191702bbc9358\">localized</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"85cd27a4521692777198d76c839cb2\">scleroderma</span> characterized by <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"d02067c4b51692777191b8eec8b062\">linear</span> patches of sclerosis, but it is not associated with Kraissl's lines.</p>",
